    "[Marketing] Competitive Marketing": [
        { q: "Competitive marketing strategy focuses on:", options: ["Ignoring competitors", "Creating a sustainable competitive advantage to outperform rivals", "Lowering prices regardless of cost", "Only advertising on TV"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Michael Porter's 'Competitive Advantage' stems from either Cost Leadership or:", options: ["Mass Production", "Differentiation", "Copying", "Exiting the market"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Market Leader' is the firm that:", options: ["Has the newest product", "Has the largest market share and usually leads in price changes and new product introductions", "Is the oldest firm", "Sells exclusively online"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Market Challenger' typically adopts which strategy?", options: ["Maintains the status quo", "Aggressively attacks the market leader to gain market share", "Focuses on a tiny niche", "Follows the leader's pricing exactly"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Frontal Attack' by a challenger involves:", options: ["Attacking the opponent's weaknesses", "Matching the opponent head-on in product, price, advertising, and distribution", "Attacking entirely new geographic areas", "Creating a completely new product category"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Flank Attack' involves:", options: ["Head-on collision", "Targeting the competitor's weak points or blind spots (e.g., underserved segments)", "Merging with the competitor", "Legal lawsuits"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Guerilla Attack' consists of:", options: ["Large-scale warfare", "Small, intermittent, unconventional attacks to harass and destabilize the competitor", "Building massive factories", "Ignoring the market"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Market Follower' prefers to:", options: ["Attack the leader constantly", "Copy or improve upon the leader's products while avoiding aggressive retaliation", "Focus on niches", "Exit the market"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Market Nicher' avoids direct competition by:", options: ["Targeting the mass market", "Serving small, specialized segments that larger firms overlook or ignore", "Lowering prices below cost", "Acquiring the market leader"], a: 1 },
        { q: "The 'Red Ocean Strategy' refers to:", options: ["Creating new demand", "Competing in existing, crowded market space where cutthroat competition turns the ocean 'bloody'", "Operating without competitors", "Focusing on environmental sustainability"], a: 1 },
        { q: "The 'Blue Ocean Strategy' aims to:", options: ["Beat competitors on price", "Make the competition irrelevant by creating new, uncontested market space and new demand", "Copy competitors precisely", "Focus solely on B2B"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Competitive Intelligence (CI) is the:", options: ["Illegal theft of trade secrets", "Legal and ethical collection and analysis of information about competitors and the market environment", "Hacking into competitor networks", "Hiring a competitor's CEO"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Benchmarking involves:", options: ["Setting internal quotas", "Comparing a company's processes and performance metrics to industry bests or best practices", "Measuring office space", "Counting employees"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Barrier to Entry' protects existing firms by:", options: ["Making it easy to start a business", "Making it difficult or costly for new competitors to enter the industry (e.g., high capital requirements, patents)", "Increasing taxes", "Banning advertising"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Economies of Scale act as a barrier to entry because:", options: ["Small firms cannot hire workers", "New entrants must enter at a large scale to be cost-competitive or face a cost disadvantage", "The government forbids small firms", "Advertising is too cheap"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Switching Costs are:", options: ["The cost of turning on lights", "The costs (financial, psychological, or effort) a consumer incurs when changing from one brand to another", "The cost to manufacture", "The retail price"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'First-Mover Advantage' can include:", options: ["High risk of technological obsolescence", "Securing key suppliers, establishing brand loyalty, and setting industry standards", "Waiting for competitors to make mistakes", "Lower R&D costs"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Value Innovation (a key concept of Blue Ocean Strategy) occurs when a company:", options: ["Only lowers costs", "Only increases buyer value", "Simultaneously pursues differentiation and low cost to create a leap in value", "Copies the competitor's value"], a: 2 },
        { q: "In analyzing competitors, assessing their 'Strategic Intent' helps you understand:", options: ["Their past profits", "Their long-term goals and how aggressively they will fight for market share", "Their office layout", "Their employee turnover"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Defense Strategy' used by a market leader (e.g., Position Defense) involves:", options: ["Attacking smaller firms", "Building fortifications around one's current territory (brand strength, patents) to keep rivals out", "Exiting the market", "Selling the company"] }
    ],
